Steve Gardner wrote:
>
>>Goldbach's conjecture belongs to a class of conjectures (previously
>>including Fermat's conjecture) which cannot be proven unprovable, since if
>>they are unprovable they are true. 
>>
>>So, if it is unprovable we will never know.
>
>Two questions: is there a proof that Goldbach's Conjecture cannot
>be proven to be unprovable? If not, then, on what basis do you claim
>that the Conjecture cannot be be proven to be unprovable?
>
>Secondly: what is 'provability'? Could it be the case that the
>Conjecture is false, but cannot be proven to be false?

It seems pretty clear to me, at least in purely theoretical terms,
that if the Goldbach conjecture is false, then it can be proven to
be false.  I'm no formal mathematician or logician, but I'll try
to be as formal as I can.

Let us assume that the Goldbach conjecture is false.  This means that
there exists an even integer N, greater than 4, which cannot be
expressed as the sum of two odd prime numbers.

In other words, for every odd prime number a<N, N-a is not prime.
It seems to me all we have to do to demonstrate that N cannot
be expressed as the sum of two odd prime numbers is to find
all odd primes a<N, and show that every N-a is composite.  (Actually,
we only need to check all primes a<=(N/2), but that doesn't affect
my proof.)

Now, we apply this test--to determine whether N can expressed
as the sum of two odd primes--to every even number beginnning with
6.  For a given N, the process terminates in a finite amount of
time (want me to prove this?  I hope it's obvious, because
it's intuitive to me, but it would take quite a bit more
work to prove it.)  Since the smallest N which is a counterexample
to Goldbach is finite, it will be found in a finite amount of time.
(Actually, I think for the proof we don't have to worry about how
we found N.  It's enough that it exists, and we can verify that
it's a counterexample to Goldbach.  But my-increasingly-less formal
proof seems stronger if we can find N in a finite time, not just
verify that it's a counterexample.)

So although the time needed to find the counterexample is unknown, if 
it exists, the time is finite.  Thus, if Goldbach is false, it
can be proved to be false.

Thus: if Goldbach cannot be proved to be false, it is true.

Thus: if Goldbach cannot be proved to be false, and cannot be
      proved to be true, it is true.

Thus: A proof that Goldbach cannot be proved to be either true or
      false is a proof that Goldbach is true; reductio ad absurdum,
      A proof that Goldbach cannot be proved to be either true or
      false does not exist.

Again, this is from a purely theoretical standpoint.  From a practical
standpoint, it may be that the smallest counterexample N is so large
that it cannot be proved to be a counterexample to Goldbach, given the
limitations on space, time, matter, and energy in the universe.

Chuck


