Charles E. Carroll wrote:
>
>So although the time needed to find the counterexample is unknown, if 
>it exists, the time is finite.  Thus, if Goldbach is false, it
>can be proved to be false.
>
>Again, this is from a purely theoretical standpoint.  From a practical
>standpoint, it may be that the smallest counterexample N is so large
>that it cannot be proved to be a counterexample to Goldbach, given the
>limitations on space, time, matter, and energy in the universe.

It is at this point in the argument that the constructionist will
want to object: concepts cannot outrun our ability to apply them,
and we must be careful to what concept of provability we appeal
here. There are a number of possibilities here, and they lead to
different strengths of constructionism:

1. The counterexample to Goldbach's Conjecture (GC) exists, but
cannot be calculated by a human being with human limitations, without
prosthetic aids (such as computers). This is very strict, and I doubt
many constructionists take this line, although Wittgenstein (who lived
before computers seems to have been tempted by it in some moods).

2. The counterexample to GC exists, but cannot be calculated even
by a prosthetically extended human being.

3. The counterexample to GC exists, but cannot be calculated by
any sentient being, even one limited only constraints of physical
law.

If (3) is the case, it seems plausible to say that GC is false but
not provably false - or to drop the claim that GC determinately
is true or false.


