Scott:
>>
Klaus> Therefore, due to a bug in the order amendment rules,
Klaus> amendments of orders are currently impossible, and the
Klaus> abovementioned amendments never occurred, so the statement of
Klaus> this CFJ is true.

I think this argument completely ignores the third paragraph of Rule
1793:

      Notwithstanding the foregoing, an Order, the purpose of which is
      to affect the operation of a prior Order, is as valid as any
      other Order, and is said to be directed at the prior Order it
      affects.

It's quite clear to me that this means that Orders to Amend do not
need to be directed at any Player, or require any Action.
<<

Good point. Of course orders, including orders to amend, need not be
directed at players - any entities can be targetted. I still believe
that the definition of orders requires that it orders some action or
other, but then I would interpret the clear language of 1793, which I
had indeed overlooked, to imply that there is _some_ sensible action
connected to an order to amend, whatever it is, and that it is
therefore possible to amend orders.

Kolja A.

